<item ID="1784483363" Creator="Beau Boorman" proto="ALG Concept" >
<attribute name="ALGId" >dot-product</attribute>
<attribute name="ALGKind" >concept</attribute>
<attribute name="ALGPrerequisites" >vectors</attribute>
<attribute name="ALGQuotedText" >Given two vectors $\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y} \in \mathbb{R}^d$, their dot product $\mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{y}$ (also known as inner product, $\langle \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}  \rangle$) is a sum over the products of the elements at the same position: $\mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{y} = \sum_{i=1}^{d} x_i y_i$.</attribute>
<attribute name="ALGSourceId" >d2l-linear-algebra</attribute>
<attribute name="ALGTags" >dot product;inner product;linear algebra;vectors</attribute>
<attribute name="ALGTitle" >Dot Product</attribute>
<attribute name="Created" >2026-07-19T12:49:19-05:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >2.5</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-07-19T12:49:19-05:00</attribute>
<attribute name="NLNames" >Aston Zhang</attribute>
<attribute name="NLOrganizations" >Lipton</attribute>
<attribute name="NLPlaces" >Alexander</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >Dot Product</attribute>
<attribute name="ScreenHeight" >67</attribute>
<attribute name="ScreenWidth" >132</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.4000000114</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.6;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;0.2;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;0.2;-0.6;0.6;-0.6;-1;0.2;-0.6;-0.8;-0.8;0.2;-0.8;0.6</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xg" >0.8480836451</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >8</attribute>
<attribute name="Yg" >0.3262047531</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >5</attribute>
<text >The dot product of two vectors sums the products of elements at corresponding positions.

Lesson: Multiply Matching Numbers, Then Add

Step 1 (core)
For two vectors—ordered lists of numbers—the dot product multiplies numbers in matching positions and adds those products together.
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Quoted passage:
The dot product of two vectors is a sum over the products of the elements at the same position

Step 2 (deep)
A dot product can represent a weighted sum, where each value is multiplied by its assigned weight.
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Quoted passage:
the weighted sum of the values in $\mathbf{x}$ according to the weights $\mathbf{w}$ could be expressed as the dot product $\mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{w}$.

Step 3 (deep)
If the weights are nonnegative and add up to 1, the dot product represents a weighted average.
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Quoted passage:
When the weights are nonnegative and sum to $1$, i.e., $\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} {w_i} = 1\right)$, the dot product expresses a weighted average.

Concept source receipt
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Given two vectors $\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y} \in \mathbb{R}^d$, their dot product $\mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{y}$ (also known as inner product, $\langle \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}  \rangle$) is a sum over the products of the elements at the same position: $\mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{y} = \sum_{i=1}^{d} x_i y_i$.

Adapted (translated to plain English; atomized into concept lessons) from Dive into Deep Learning — 2.3 Linear Algebra by Aston Zhang, Zachary C. Lipton, Mu Li, and Alexander J. Smola, CC-BY-SA-4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/).</text>
