<text >A vector norm provides a scalar measure of the vector&apos;s magnitude.

Lesson: How Big a Vector Is

Step 1 (core)
A vector norm tells us how big a vector is.
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Quoted passage:
Informally, the norm of a vector tells us how big it is.

Step 2 (core)
It measures the magnitude of the vector’s components, not how many components it has.
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Quoted passage:
Here, we are employing a notion of size that concerns the magnitude of a vector&apos;s components (not its dimensionality).

Step 3 (core)
A norm is a function that turns a vector into a single number, called a scalar.
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Quoted passage:
A norm is a function $\| \cdot \|$ that maps a vector to a scalar

Step 4 (deep)
Different valid norms can represent different ideas of size.
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Quoted passage:
Many functions are valid norms and different norms encode different notions of size.

Concept source receipt
Source: d2l-linear-algebra
Informally, the norm of a vector tells us how big it is.

Adapted (translated to plain English; atomized into concept lessons) from Dive into Deep Learning — 2.3 Linear Algebra by Aston Zhang, Zachary C. Lipton, Mu Li, and Alexander J. Smola, CC-BY-SA-4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/).</text>
